National Park Data Project

Laura Maple

2023

Our National Parks have some of the best views, coolest geology, and most diverse species. I love travel and the outdoors and have combined those hobbies into a love for our National Parks. There are currently 63 parks, with the newest being New River Gorge in West Virginia (established 2020). I wanted to look at data for a few different aspects to our parks, such as annual visitation, land area, and location. I used data from the following three sources: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_national_parks_of_the_United_States, https://www.nps.gov/subjects/lwcf/acreagereports.htm, https://irma.nps.gov/Stats/Reports/National. The tables and plots below were created with Rstudio.

My first step was importing the annual visitation data for each park. Unfortunately, this data included every NPS site (National Historic Sites, National Monuments, etc.), so I had to filter through the data for only the National Parks. Then, I added 5, 10, and 15 year means for each parks annual visitation. I then did the same with percent increases.

visitor.data <- read.csv("AnnualVisitationByPark.csv", 
                         check.names = FALSE, col.names = c("Park Name", 2008:2022))
parknamefile <- read.csv("list_of_park_names.csv", header = FALSE)
park_names <- c(parknamefile$V1)
#import a list of park names as a vector

park.data <- visitor.data %>% filter(str_detect(visitor.data$"Park Name", paste(park_names, collapse = "|")))
#only want National Parks, not all NPS sites

park.data$"15-year mean" <- rowMeans(park.data[ , 2:16], na.rm = TRUE)
park.data$"10-year mean" <- rowMeans(park.data[ , 7:16], na.rm = TRUE)
park.data$"5-year mean" <- rowMeans(park.data[ , 12:16], na.rm = TRUE)
#adding columns with some means of annual visitation

percent_increase <- function(new.num, og.num) {
  return (((new.num - og.num)/og.num) * 100)
}
park.data$"5-year % increase" <- percent_increase(park.data[ , 16], park.data[ , 12])
park.data$"10-year % increase" <- percent_increase(park.data[ , 16], park.data[ , 7])
park.data$"15-year % increase" <- percent_increase(park.data[ , 16], park.data[ , 2])
#created  function to measure percent increases in annual visitation between two years
#then applied it to 3 pairs: a 5-year, 10-year, and 15-year spread

park.data <- rbind(park.data[1 , ], park.data[44 , ], park.data[2:43 , ], park.data[45:63 , ])
rownames(park.data) = 1:63
#rearranging park.data so that the order of the parks is alphabetical with American Samoa being 2nd

My next step was importing acreage data. This data also includes all NPS sites, so I had to filter through this data as well. I also realized about halfway through tidying this data that parks with a National Preserve part of the park had two entries in the data: one for the preserve and one for the park. I decided to combine those acreage entries because they are part of the same park system. Then I added the acreage to our main table: park.data.

combine_nps_sites <- function(df, x, y){
  df[y , 2] <- df[x , 2] + df[y , 2]
  df <- df[-x , ]
}
temp.data <- combine_nps_sites(temp.data, 16, 17)

I found two tables from Wikipedia that I wanted to use. One table had location data and the date each park was established. This data uploaded from the csv file in a very messy way, so I had to use string functions to extract the state/territory of each park as well as the longitude and latitude. The date was easier; I simply had to convert to a date/time format. Finally, I inner joined the cleaned up table with park.data.

wikidata <- read.csv("wiki NP table.csv", check.names = FALSE)
rownames(wikidata) = 1:63
wikidata <- wikidata %>% select("Name", "Location", "Date established as park")
location.data <- c(wikidata$Location)

#found a table on wikipedia that listed location of parks and the date each was est.

wikidata$"State(s) or Territory" <- sub("\n.*", "", location.data)
#location data was a mess so I used cat(location.data) many times
#wanted to extract the state/territory from the coordinates

location.data <- str_split(location.data, '/') %>% sapply(., "[[", 3)
location.data <- sub(".*", "", location.data) %>% sub(" ", "", .) %>% str_split(., ";")
wikidata$"Latitude" <- sapply(location.data, "[[", 1) %>% as.numeric()
wikidata$"Longitude" <- sapply(location.data, "[[", 2) %>% sub(" ", "", .) %>% as.numeric()
#pulled out the latitudinal/longitudinal coordinates and sent them to separate columns

wikidata <- wikidata[ , -2]
#got rid of the messy location column 

wikidata$`Date established as park` <- wikidata$`Date established as park` %>%  as.Date(., "%B %d, %Y")
#converted date column to date/time format
wikidata$Name <- park.data$`Park Name`
#replaced the names with the same column from park.data 
colnames(wikidata)[1] = "Park Name"
park.data <- inner_join(park.data, wikidata, by = "Park Name")
#joined the two dataframes together

I was curious if a park being close to other parks increased visitation. In order to do that, I had to move the coordinates to a separate table and find the distance between each park. Then I took the 5 closest parks and averaged them to get the average distance of the 5 closest parks to each park.

coords <- park.data %>% select("Longitude", "Latitude")
#wanted to isolate just the coordinates 
head(coords)
##   Longitude Latitude
## 1    -68.21    44.35
## 2   -170.68   -14.25
## 3   -109.57    38.68
## 4   -102.50    43.75
## 5   -103.25    29.25
## 6    -80.08    25.65
distmatrix <- distm(coords, fun = distGeo) %>% as.data.frame()
#used geosphere package to calculate distance in meters between every park
rownames(distmatrix) = 1:63
colnames(distmatrix) = 1:63
distmatrix[distmatrix == 0] <- NA
head(distmatrix[ , 1:6])
##          1        2         3         4       5        6
## 1       NA 12092378 3471603.4 2728573.1 3510361  2334743
## 2 12092378       NA 8637110.9 9422271.8 8691355 10748382
## 3  3471603  8637111        NA  817079.1 1197236  3114878
## 4  2728573  9422272  817079.1        NA 1610449  2854395
## 5  3510361  8691355 1197235.8 1610448.6      NA  2321006
## 6  2334743 10748382 3114878.1 2854395.4 2321006       NA
meanmin <- function(nums){
  mean(sort(nums)[1:5], na.rm = TRUE)
}
#created a function to find the closest 5 parks and average the distance

distancelist <- apply(distmatrix, 1, meanmin)
park.data$"Average distance of 5 nearest parks (m)" <- distancelist
#added the mean distance of 5 closest parks to park.data

The chart below shows a timeline of when each park was established as a National Park. Many parks were owned by the government before this date, but they may have been National Monuments, for example.

park.data %>% 
  mutate(`Park Name` = fct_reorder(`Park Name`, `Date established as park`)) %>%  
  #wanted the chart to be in order of dates 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(y = `Date established as park`, x = `Park Name`)) +
  geom_segment(aes(x = `Park Name`, xend = `Park Name`, y = structure(-Inf, class = "Date"), 
                    yend = `Date established as park`), color = "royalblue4") +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_point(color = "royalblue4", size = 2) +
  theme_bw() +

The map below plots each park and shows the relative size and popularity of each park. The very dark park in the Eastern continental US is Great Smokey Mountains. We can also note that the Alaska parks all have significant acreage to them.

us.map <- map_data("state") %>% select(long, lat, group, id = region)
#creates state map I used in combination with the world map
world.map <- map_data("world") %>% select(long, lat, group, id = region)
#this creates the world map 
#(because the US state map does not include Alaska/Hawaii, let alone the US territories)

world.map %>% filter(str_detect(world.map$id, "American Samoa|Virgin Islands|USA")) %>% 
  #I wanted to only map the US + American Samoa + US Virgin Islands
ggplot(aes(long, lat, group = group)) + 
  geom_polygon(alpha = 0.5, fill = "white") +
  geom_path(color = "gray") +
  coord_equal() +
  scale_fill_identity() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  #world map base
  geom_polygon(us.map, mapping = aes(long, lat, group = group), alpha = 0, fill = "white", color = "gray") +
  #overlayed the state outlines
  geom_point(park.data, mapping = aes(`Longitude`, `Latitude`, size = `Acreage`/1000000, color = `5-year mean`/1000000), 
             alpha = 1, inherit.aes = FALSE) + 
  #added the coordinates of the parks
  #made the color reflect average annual visitation over 2018-2022
  #made the size reflect acreage
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#00d4ff", high = "black") +
  xlim(-200,-50) +
  ylim(-20,75) +
  #cut down the map since I only needed a portion of it
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", title = "Map of US National Parks", 
       color = "Average Annual Visitors '18-'22 (Millions)", size = "Acres (Millions)") +
  geom_label(label="American Samoa", x = -175, y = -10) +
  geom_label(label="US Virgin Islands", x = -60, y = 12.5) +
  geom_label(label="Hawaii", x = -165, y = 27)
